Registers.Documentation: The operation of the PORTA_DATA register depends on whether the bit/pin is in output mode or input mode. In both modes, a set bit in the PORTA_DATA register corresponds to a signal high on a GPIO pin. A cleared bit in the PORTA_DATA register corresponds to a signal low on a GPIO pin. $[/p$]$[p$]The PORTA_DATA, ${.:DATA_SET}, and ${.:DATA_CLR} registers control the state of GPIO pins in output mode. To enable output mode (and output drivers), use the ${.:DIR_SET} and ${.:DIR_CLR} registers. $[/p$]$[p$]Writes to the PORTA_DATA register affect the state of all pins of the port that are in output mode. To set or clear specific pins without impacting other pins of the port, use the ${.:DATA_SET} and ${.:DATA_CLR} registers. $[/p$]$[p$]When the GPIO pins are in input mode (input driver is enabled with the ${.:INEN} register), reads from the PORTA_DATA, ${.:DATA_SET}, and ${.:DATA_CLR} registers return the state of the respective GPIO pins.  $[/p$]$[p$]Note that when the input driver is not enabled, reads from the PORTA_DATA, ${.:DATA_SET}, and ${.:DATA_CLR} registers return the value previously written to the registers.

Registers.Documentation: The PORTA_DIR, ${.:DIR_SET}, and ${.:DIR_CLR} registers select output or input mode for GPIO pins and enable output drivers. Use the ${.:INEN}, ${.:INEN_SET}, and ${.:INEN_CLR} registers to enable or disable input drivers. $[/p$]$[p$]Writes to the PORTA_DIR register affect the state of all pins of the port. To select a direction for specific pins without impacting other pins of the port, use the ${.:DIR_SET} and ${.:DIR_CLR} registers. $[/p$]$[p$]Setting a bit in the PORTA_DIR register enables output mode on the corresponding a GPIO pin. Clearing a bit in the PORTA_DIR register disables output mode on the corresponding GPIO pin. $[/p$]$[p$]Input Mode - The default mode of every GPIO pin after reset is the input mode, but the input drivers are not enabled. To enable GPIO input drivers, set the corresponding bits in the ${.:INEN} register. When enabled, a read from the ${.:DATA} register returns the logical state of the input pin. The input signal does not overwrite the state of the bit used for the output case. That state can only be altered by software. If the input driver is enabled, a write to the ${.:DATA} register can alter the state of the bit, but the change cannot be read back. $[/p$]$[p$]Output Mode - Any GPIO pin can be configured for output mode. The GPIO output drivers are enabled by setting the corresponding bits in the PORTA_DIR, ${.:DIR_SET}, or ${.:DIR_CLR} registers.  By using the ${.:DIR_SET} and ${.:DIR_CLR} registers, the direction of the signal flow of individual GPIO pins can be altered by separate software threads without mutually impacting other GPIOs on the same port. Both registers return the same value when read. Because the state of the GPIO output can already be controlled before the output driver is enabled, it is recommended to first set or clear the bit (using the ${.:DATA}, ${.:DATA_SET}, or ${.:DATA_CLR} registers) to avoid any volatile levels on the output. $[/p$]$[p$]Open-Drain Mode - Every GPIO can also be used in open-drain mode. To accomplish this, first, clear the respective bit in the ${.:DATA} or ${.:DATA_CLR} register. Then, set the one bit in the ${.:INEN} register. Reads from the ${.:DATA} register then return the status from the pin and do not return the state of the internal flip-flop. By toggling the output driver through the ${.:DIR_SET} and ${.:DIR_CLR} register pair, the output signal can be pulled low or three-stated as required. Note that the polarity of the driven signal can be inverted when the internal flip-flop is set instead. When a GPIO port is used in open-drain mode, take care to not exceed the V$[sub$]IH$[/sub$] operating condition associated with the respective pin.

Registers.Documentation: The PORTA_FER register bits indicate each port bit's operating mode: general purpose I/O mode or peripheral mode. After reset, all pins default to GPIO mode. Setting a bit in the PORTA_FER registers enables a peripheral module to take ownership of the pin. The function enable bits impact output control only. Regardless of the setting of the function enable bits, both GPIO and peripherals can still sense the pin input. After a function is enabled, it is up to the ${.:MUX} registers as to which peripheral takes control.

Registers.Documentation: The PORTA_INEN, ${.:INEN_SET}, and ${.:INEN_CLR} registers enable or disable input drivers, which are required for using a GPIO pin in input mode. $[/p$]$[p$]Writes to the PORTA_INEN register affect the input drivers for all pins of the port. To set or clear specific pin drivers without impacting other pin drivers of the port, use the ${.:INEN_SET} and ${.:INEN_CLR} registers. $[/p$]$[p$]If the input is enabled, reads from the ${.:DATA}, ${.:DATA_SET}, or ${.:DATA_CLR} registers return the state of the pins. However, the state of the output is not overwritten by the input. It is altered by software writes only. Input and output drivers can be enabled at the same time. In this case, a read of the data register returns the true value of the data register and not the pin state. $[/p$]$[p$]For more information, see the ${.:DATA} register description and the ${.:DIR} register description.

Registers.Documentation: When a pin is in peripheral mode (not GPIO mode), the PORTA_MUX register controls which peripheral takes ownership of a pin. Ports may have multiple, different peripheral functions. Two bits are required to describe every multiplexer on an individual pin-by-pin scheme. For example, bit 0 and bit 1 of the PORTA_MUX register control the multiplexer of pin 0, bit 2 and bit 3 of PORTA_MUX control the multiplexer of pin 1, and so on. The value of any PORTA_MUX bit has no effect on the port pins when the associated bit in the ${.:FER} register is 0 (selects GPIO mode). Even if a port has only one function, the ${.:MUX} register is still present. For single function ports (no multiplexing is needed), leave the ${.:MUX} bits at 0 (default). For all PORTA_MUX bit fields: 00 = default/reset peripheral option, 01 = first alternate peripheral option, 10 = second alternate peripheral option, and 11 = third alternate peripheral option.$[/p$]$[p$]See the processor data sheet for details regarding the peripheral options associated with each port.

To invert polarity of peripheral signals, use the inversion selection programming in the signal's corresponding module.  $[/p$]$[p$]Writes to the PORTA_POL register affect the polarity inversion selection of all pins of the port. To enable or disable polarity inversion for specific pins without impacting other pins of the port, use the ${.:POL_SET} and ${.:POL_CLR} registers. $[/p$]$[p$]Setting a bit in the PORTA_POL register enables polarity inversion on the corresponding inversion GPIO pin, making the pin active-low or falling-edge sensitive. Clearing a bit in the PORTA_POL register disables polarity (default state) on the corresponding GPIO pin, making it active-high or rising-edge sensitive.

Registers.Documentation: The PORTD_DIR, ${.:DIR_SET}, and ${.:DIR_CLR} registers select output or input mode for GPIO pins and enable output drivers. Use the ${.:INEN}, ${.:INEN_SET}, and ${.:INEN_CLR} registers to enable or disable input drivers. $[/p$]$[p$]Writes to the PORTD_DIR register affect the state of all pins of the port. To select a direction for specific pins without impacting other pins of the port, use the ${.:DIR_SET} and ${.:DIR_CLR} registers. $[/p$]$[p$]Setting a bit in the PORTD_DIR register enables output mode on the corresponding a GPIO pin. Clearing a bit in the PORTD_DIR register disables output mode on the corresponding GPIO pin. $[/p$]$[p$]Input Mode - The default mode of every GPIO pin after reset is the input mode, but the input drivers are not enabled. To enable GPIO input drivers, set the corresponding bits in the ${.:INEN} register. When enabled, a read from the ${.:DATA} register returns the logical state of the input pin. The input signal does not overwrite the state of the bit used for the output case. That state can only be altered by software. If the input driver is enabled, a write to the ${.:DATA} register can alter the state of the bit, but the change cannot be read back. $[/p$]$[p$]Output Mode - Any GPIO pin can be configured for output mode. The GPIO output drivers are enabled by setting the corresponding bits in the PORTD_DIR, ${.:DIR_SET}, or ${.:DIR_CLR} registers.  By using the ${.:DIR_SET} and ${.:DIR_CLR} registers, the direction of the signal flow of individual GPIO pins can be altered by separate software threads without mutually impacting other GPIOs on the same port. Both registers return the same value when read. Because the state of the GPIO output can already be controlled before the output driver is enabled, it is recommended to first set or clear the bit (using the ${.:DATA}, ${.:DATA_SET}, or ${.:DATA_CLR} registers) to avoid any volatile levels on the output. $[/p$]$[p$]Open-Drain Mode - Every GPIO can also be used in open-drain mode. To accomplish this, first, clear the respective bit in the ${.:DATA} or ${.:DATA_CLR} register. Then, set the one bit in the ${.:INEN} register. Reads from the ${.:DATA} register then return the status from the pin and do not return the state of the internal flip-flop. By toggling the output driver through the ${.:DIR_SET} and ${.:DIR_CLR} register pair, the output signal can be pulled low or three-stated as required. Note that the polarity of the driven signal can be inverted when the internal flip-flop is set instead. When a GPIO port is used in open-drain mode, take care to not exceed the V$[sub$]IH$[/sub$] operating condition associated with the respective pin.

Registers.Documentation: When a pin is in peripheral mode (not GPIO mode), the PORTD_MUX register controls which peripheral takes ownership of a pin. Ports may have multiple, different peripheral functions. Two bits are required to describe every multiplexer on an individual pin-by-pin scheme. Even if a port has only one function, the ${.:MUX} register is still present. For single function ports (no multiplexing is needed), leave the ${.:MUX} bits at 0 (default).
